flowRoot.flowPara: Between September 1, 1999 and October 1, 2009 1339 individuals served as a PI or Co-PI on National Science Foundation grants awarded to the University of Michigan. By plotting these individuals and their ties to other investigators on University of Michigan-lead NSF projects, a social network structure of the UM NSF Investigator community emerges. The largest group of interconnected researchers, or giant component, consists of 443 individuals and 1493 links between individuals representing co-investigator-ship.

The network structure of the UM NSF Investigator community can be leveraged to further explore community structures within the giant component. For instance, the Newman-Girvan Betweenness Clustering algorithm segments large network structures into smaller community structures by identifying specific network links with high betweenness, which serve as brokerage points where a relatively large number of individuals are connected to a larger network through a relatively small number of ties. Using this algorithm, the UM NSF Investigator community giant component can be divided into 8 smaller, interconnected subcommunities.

By examining the membership of these community clusters, we can categorize the types of research interests that each community contains. By rescaling the visualization, we can understand the relative size of these subcommunities, how they are connected and can gain insight into how to further investigate the roles that physical and virtual obstacles play in shaping the structure of this research community.
